# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: djenging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:djenging/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:djenging/alingano-maisu] The concept for *Alingano Maisu* came about in 2001 when two Hawaiian voyaging groups, the Polynesian Voyaging Society and Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi, met with Piailug.
[src:djenging/alingano-maisu] The two hulls of the 56-foot (17 m) vessel were fabricated by the Friends of *Hōkūleʻa* and *Hawaiʻiloa* on Oʻahu and shipped to the Island of Hawaiʻi where Na Kalai Waʻa completed construction of the canoe.
[src:djenging/alingano-maisu] The Polynesian Voyaging Society provided much of the funding for the voyaging aspect of the project as well as an escort boat to help sail the canoe to Satawal.
[src:djenging/alingano-maisu] The canoe is home-ported on the island of Yap under the command of Piailug's son, Sesario Sewralur.
[src:djenging/alingano-maisu] Accompanied by *Hōkūleʻa*, the *Maisu* left Kawaihae, Hawaii, on January 18, 2007.
[src:djenging/alingano-maisu] After stops in the Marshall Islands, Pohnpei, and Chuuk, the Maisu reached Satawal on March 15, 2007.
[src:djenging/alingano-maisu] On March 18, while on Satawal, five native Hawaiian navigators on the voyage were inducted into pwo, a sacred Micronesian brotherhood of master navigators.
[src:djenging/alingano-maisu] In June 2008, Palau Community College announced that there will be a one-year program in traditional non-instrumental navigation on the *Alingano Maisu* under Sesario Sewralur.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The **New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa** is a maritime museum in Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] It is located on Hobson Wharf, adjacent to the Viaduct Harbour in central Auckland.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] It houses exhibitions spanning New Zealand's maritime history, from the first Polynesian explorers and settlers to modern day triumphs at the America's Cup.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The museum focuses on maritime stories of both the Auckland Region and New Zealand, with displays covering topics including immigration, trade, design, innovation, leisure, maritime history, Polynesian voyagers, and the history of the America's Cup.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In addition to displays and art exhibitions, the New Zealand Maritime Museum collections include historic and cultural artifacts, replicas and working heritage vessels.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The New Zealand Maritime Museum is located on Hobson Wharf on the Auckland waterfront, adjacent to the Viaduct Basin and Princes Wharf.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The entrance of the museum incorporates the Launchman's Building, a structure built in 1920 which formerly housed a number of small boating companies.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The old Launchman's Building (Launch Offices) gained a Category II listing from Heritage New Zealand in 1981.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The main section of the maritime museum in an industrial-inspired structure located on Hobson Wharf.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Heritage vessels owned by the museum are moored at the museum marina, and launched for sailings around the Waitematā Harbour.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 2010, the building won the Auckland Architecture Awards by the New Zealand Institute of Architects.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Located outside of the Maritime Museum's entrance is *KZ1*, a yacht built to compete in the 1988 America's Cup, gifted to the museum by Fay Richwhite in 1990.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Currently known as New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, the museum opened in 1993 as Hobson Wharf: Auckland Maritime Museum.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 1996, the museum was renamed the New Zealand National Maritime Museum, a name given by Prime Minister Jim Bolger.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The museum rebranded as Voyager New Zealand Maritime Museum in November 2009, in order to reflect the museum's focus on exploration and discovery.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The organisation's current name, New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, was adopted in 2014.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The organisation's Māori language name, Hui te Ananui a Tangaroa, was gifted by Hugh Kāwharu of Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, and means "the Dwelling of Tangaroa", the atua of the oceans.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The establishment of a maritime history museum in Auckland began as a proposal by members of the Auckland Maritime Society, including Bill Laxon, Bob Hawkins, Cliff Hawkins and John Street, and by former members of the Auckland Harbour Board and Union Steam Ship Company.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The society had been established in 1958 as a section of the Auckland Institute and Museum, focused on promoting the study of ships.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 1973, the society explored the possibility of establishing a maritime museum on the shores of Lake Pupuke, which was found to be unsuitable.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In November 1981, the Auckland Maritime Museum was established as a charitable trust.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The Auckland Ferry Terminal, where the museum had been storing archival materials, was explored as a potential site for the museum, but due to the cost of renovations this was decided against.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 1984, the museum appointed a director, Gordon Stevenson, former director of the Queen Elizabeth II Army Memorial Museum, and had begun exploring the possibility of using sheds on Princes Wharf.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Plans for a smaller Princes Wharf museum were halted when the Auckland Harbour Board decided to redevelop Hobson Wharf, with the museum becoming a major part of the redevelopment.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 1989, Rodney Wilson was appointed as the new director for the museum, who led fundraising efforts to establish the institution.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Plans for the museum at Hobson Wharf were announced in February 1989, with construction on the museum beginning in mid-1992.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The museum opened in August 1993, at an estimated cost of NZ$11.1 million.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Many of the early maritime collections were long-term loans from Auckland War Memorial Museum, or donated items by members of the Auckland Maritime Society.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] While originally focusing on Auckland, the museum later expanded to become a national maritime museum.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] By 1996, financial difficulties led to staff redundancies at the museum, with museum director Richard Cassels resigning during the financial difficulties in 1998.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 2001, the New Zealand Government funded the Pacific Discovery Experience, a virtual reality exhibition depicting both the discovery of New Zealand by Polynesian peoples, and the later discovery by Europeans.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] A NZ$8 million extension to the northern end of the museum was built in 2009 to house a permanent exhibition, *Blue Water, Black Magic*, about Sir Peter Blake.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] It includes the original *NZL 32* (*Black Magic*).
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] *Blue Water, Black Magic* was developed in collaboration with Te Papa and Blake's daughter Sarah-Jane Blake.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 2010, an extension was added to the museum, housing an exhibition to New Zealand yachting which includes *NZL 32*, the yacht which won the 1995 America's Cup, suspended in the centre of the space.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] By 2018, the museum received approximately 160,000 annual visitors.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The museum was run by New Zealand National Maritime Museum Trust Board until March 2018, when it became a part of Regional Facilities Auckland, an Auckland Council-controlled organisation.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The organisation is now run by Tātaki Auckland Unlimited, the economic development agency of Auckland.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 2008, the Auckland Regional Amenities Funding Act was established, which ensured that funding for the New Zealand Maritime Museum was spread across all local councils in the Auckland Region.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] As of 2021, funding for the organisation primarily comes from the Auckland Council.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The first director of the Auckland Maritime Museum Trust was Gordon Stevenson, who was employed in January 1985.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Rodney Wilson became the museum director in 1989, who was the director of the museum when it opened in 1993.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 1994, Wilson left to become the director of the Auckland War Memorial Museum.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Wilson was replaced by Richard Cassels in the same year, who left in 1998.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Cassels was followed by chief executive Larry Robbins in 1999, Craig Hobbs in 2007, and Paul Evans in 2008.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] By 2013, Murray Reade had become the chief executive officer.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 2013, former director of Toitū Otago Settlers Museum, Linda Wigley, became the director of the maritime museum, overseeing the redevelopment of the museum until her resignation in June 2014.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The current director of the maritime museum, Vincent Lipanovich, has held the position since 2015.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In 2018, the institution had 166 volunteers, working as tour guides, maintenance and operational crew for heritage vessels, model makers and learning programme assistants.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Since 2003, personnel from the Royal New Zealand Navy have been occasionally seconded to the museum to assist with maintenance of the ships and exhibition objects.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] In addition, the museum holds collection items focusing on subjects including whaling, modern commercial shipping, lifeboat, pilotage and coastguard services, marine surveying, maritime arts and crafts and maritime recreation.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The museum also operates *Aotearoa One*, launched 2013, described on the museum's website as "a modern take on a traditional waka", which no longer has scheduled sailings.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The museum previously operated the *Rapaki steam crane*, a 1926 floating steam crane, built at Paisley in Scotland for the Lyttelton Harbour Board, which was permanently removed and dismantled in December 2018.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The vessel had been used in active service for three years during World War II, being used to support the United States Navy at New Caledonia.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] The museum has a collection of over 130 watercraft, including the 1933 John L.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Hacker-designed mahogany and kauri speedboat *Jon-El*, *The Frances*, an early 20th century vessel owned by the Shakespear family, and Paul Caffyn's kayak *Isadora*.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] Other vessels include the *Tainui*, an 1860 whaling vessel, P-class sailing dinghies designed by Harry Highet, *Mammoth*, a moth-class dinghy, and the Karlich hull used by Olympic Gold medalist rowers, the 1972 New Zealand eight.
[src:djenging/aotearoa-one] *Tatarai*, a Baurua voyager canoe from Kiribati built in 1976 by Kiribati islanders and photographer Jim Siers using traditional methods, and sailed from Kiribati to Fiji in 1976, is also held in the museum's collections.
[src:djenging/apilan] Apilan is a native Malay word, not descended from any foreign word.
[src:djenging/apilan] It is also a standalone word, because the syllable is api-lan instead of apil-an.
[src:djenging/apilan] The term comes from Malay word *kota* which in turn comes from the Sanskrit word कोट्ट (kota) which means fort, fortress, castle, fortified house, fortification, works, city, town, or place encircled by walls.
[src:djenging/apilan] The word *mara* may come from Malay word meaning "appear before", "forward", "come", "moved to the front", "forward", and "advanced".
[src:djenging/apilan] Thus it can be interpreted as "breastwork before a cannon" or "breastwork at the front".
[src:djenging/apilan] According to the Great Indonesian Dictionary (KBBI), kota mara means (1) Wall on a ship to protect men mounting the cannon (2) Terrace or wall over a castle which a cannon is mounted.
[src:djenging/apilan] Warington Smyth, kota mara means transverse deck bulkhead at stem and stern (of a ship).
[src:djenging/apilan] *Benteng* itself means fort, battery, or redoubt.
[src:djenging/apilan] Singapore resident John Crawfurd recorded Malay piracy near Singapore waters.
[src:djenging/apilan] The Malay pirate ships of the time were 40–50 feet (12–15 m) long with 15-foot (4.6 m) beam.
[src:djenging/apilan] The decks were made of split *nibong* wood.
[src:djenging/apilan] Smaller pirate craft put up thick plank bulwarks [apilan] when fighting, while larger ones like those of the Lanun people had bamboo ledges hanging over their gunwales, with a protecting breastwork [kota mara] of plaited rattan about 3 feet (0.91 meters) high.
[src:djenging/apilan] A crew might consist of 20–30 men, augmented with oarsmen of captured slaves.
[src:djenging/apilan] Small craft would have nine oars per side; larger ones would be double-banked, with an upper tier of oarsmen seated on the bulwark projection hidden behind rattan breastwork.
[src:djenging/apilan] Pirate armament included a stockade near the bow, with iron or brass 4-pounders, and another stockade aft, generally with two swivel guns.
[src:djenging/apilan] They also might have four or five brass swivels, or rantaka, on each side.
[src:djenging/apilan] They have bamboo shields, and were armed with spears, keris, muskets and other firearms they could get.
[src:djenging/armadahan] The single outrigger float (*palangoy*) on the starboard side was either two bamboo poles lashed together or a flattened elongated beam.
[src:djenging/armadahan] It was connected to the hull by a length of bamboo around 6 m (20 ft) long, known as the *batangan*.
[src:djenging/armadahan] It also featured a counter-balance beam projecting off the port side known as the *paltek*.
[src:djenging/armadahan] The *batangan* is connected to the hull by a wooden outrigger beam collar, with braces on the forward, cross, and aft.
[src:djenging/armadahan] At the stern is a small socket for the rudder tiller.
[src:djenging/armadahan] Three or four other small holes are also drilled along the midcenter of the dugout to let the water enter the craft, allowing live fish to be stored in the hull when fishing.
[src:djenging/armadahan] These holes are also used to drain the craft when beached.
[src:djenging/armadahan] Each boat also has a cooking area on the aft, usually a wood or kerosene portable stove.
[src:djenging/armadahan] In modern times, these types of boats are usually motorized or paddled.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They also include indigenous ethnic minorities in Vietnam, Cambodia, Myanmar, Thailand, Hainan, and the Torres Strait Islands.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The nations and territories predominantly populated by Austronesian-speaking peoples are sometimes known collectively as **Austronesia**.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The group originated from a prehistoric seaborne migration, known as the Austronesian expansion, from Taiwan, circa 3000 to 1500 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Austronesians reached the Batanes Islands in the northernmost Philippines by around 2200 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They used sails some time before 2000 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In conjunction with their use of other maritime technologies (notably catamarans, outrigger boats, lashed-lug boats, and the crab claw sail), this enabled phases of rapid dispersal into the islands of the Indo-Pacific, culminating in the settlement of New Zealand c.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] During the initial part of the migrations, they encountered and assimilated (or were assimilated by) the Paleolithic populations that had migrated earlier into Maritime Southeast Asia and New Guinea.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They reached as far as Easter Island to the east, Madagascar to the west, and New Zealand to the south.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] At the furthest extent, they might have also reached the Americas.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Aside from language, Austronesian peoples widely share cultural characteristics, including such traditions and traditional technologies as lashed-lug shipbuilding, tattooing, stilt houses, jade carving, wetland agriculture, and various rock art motifs.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They also share domesticated plants and animals that were carried along with the migrations, including rice, bananas, coconuts, breadfruit, *Dioscorea* yams, taro, paper mulberry, chickens, pigs, and dogs.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The linguistic connections between Madagascar, Polynesia, and Southeast Asia, particularly the similarities between Malagasy, Malay, and Polynesian numerals, were recognized early in the colonial era by European authors.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] German naturalist Johann Reinhold Forster, who traveled with James Cook on his second voyage, also recognized the similarities of Polynesian languages to those of Island Southeast Asia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In his book *Observations Made during a Voyage round the World* (1778), he posited that the ultimate origins of the Polynesians might have been the lowland regions of the Philippines and proposed that they arrived to the islands via long-distance voyaging.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Multiple other authors corroborated this classification (except for the erroneous inclusion of Maldivian), and the language family came to be known as "Malayo-Polynesian", first coined by the German linguist Franz Bopp in 1841 (German: *malayisch-polynesisch*).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The connections between Southeast Asia, Madagascar, and the Pacific Islands were also noted by other European explorers, including the Orientalist William Marsden and the naturalist Johann Reinhold Forster.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Johann Friedrich Blumenbach added Austronesians as the fifth category to his "varieties" of humans in the second edition of *De Generis Humani Varietate Nativa* (1781).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] He initially grouped them by geography and thus called Austronesians the "people from the southern world".
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In the third edition, published in 1795, he named Austronesians the "Malay race", or the "brown race", after correspondence with Joseph Banks, who was part of the first voyage of James Cook.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Blumenbach used the term "Malay" due to his belief that most Austronesians spoke the "Malay idiom" (i.e., the Austronesian languages), though he inadvertently caused the later confusion of his racial category with the Malay ethnic group.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The other varieties Blumenbach identified were the "Caucasians" (white), "Mongolians" (yellow), "Ethiopians" (black), and "Americans" (red).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Blumenbach's definition of the "Malay" race is largely identical to the modern distribution of the Austronesian peoples, including not only Islander Southeast Asians but also the people of Madagascar and the Pacific Islands.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Although Blumenbach's work was later used in scientific racism, Blumenbach was a monogenist and did not believe the human "varieties" were inherently inferior to each other.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Rather, he believed that the Malay race was a combination of the "Ethiopian" and "Caucasian" varieties.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] — Johann Friedrich Blumenbach,*The anthropological treatises of Johann Friedrich Blumenbach*, translated by Thomas Bendyshe, 1865.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] By the 19th century, however, a classification of Austronesians as being a subset of the "Mongolian" race was favored, as was polygenism.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The British naturalist James Cowles Prichard originally followed Blumenbach by treating Papuans and Indigenous Australians as being descendants of the same stock as Austronesians.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] But by his third edition of *Researches into the Physical History of Man* (1836–1847), his work had become more racialized due to the influence of polygenism.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] He classified the peoples of Austronesia into two groups: the "Malayo-Polynesians" (roughly equivalent to the Austronesian peoples) and the "Kelænonesians" (roughly equivalent to the Australo-Melanesians).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] He further subdivided the latter into the "Alfourous" (also "Haraforas" or "Alfoërs", the Native Australians), and the "Pelagian or Oceanic Negroes" (the Melanesians and western Polynesians).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Despite this, he acknowledges that "Malayo-Polynesians" and "Pelagian Negroes" had "remarkable characters in common", particularly in terms of language and craniometry.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In linguistics, the Malayo-Polynesian language family also initially excluded Melanesia and Micronesia, due to the perceived physical differences between the inhabitants of these regions from Malayo-Polynesian speakers.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] However, there was growing evidence of their linguistic relationship to Malayo-Polynesian languages, notably from studies on the Melanesian languages by Georg von der Gabelentz, Robert Henry Codrington, and Sidney Herbert Ray.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Codrington coined and used the term "Ocean" language family rather than "Malayo-Polynesian" in 1891, in opposition to the exclusion of Melanesian and Micronesian languages.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] This was adopted by Ray, who defined the "Oceanic" language family as encompassing the languages of Southeast Asia and Madagascar, Micronesia, Melanesia, and Polynesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In 1899, the Austrian linguist and ethnologist Wilhelm Schmidt coined the term "Austronesian" (German: *austronesisch*, from Latin *auster*, "south wind"; and Greek *νῆσος*, "island") to refer to the language family.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Schmidt had the same motivations as Codrington: he proposed the term as a replacement to "Malayo-Polynesian", because he also opposed the implied exclusion of the languages of Melanesia and Micronesia in the latter name.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] It became the accepted name for the language family, with Oceanic and Malayo-Polynesian languages being retained as names for subgroups.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The term "Austronesian", or more accurately "Austronesian-speaking peoples", came to refer to people who speak the languages of the Austronesian language family.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Some authors, however, object to the use of the term to refer to people, as they question whether there really is any biological or cultural shared ancestry between all Austronesian-speaking groups.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] This is especially true for authors who reject the prevailing "Out of Taiwan" hypothesis and instead offer scenarios where the Austronesian languages spread among preexisting static populations through borrowing or convergence, with little or no population movements.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Despite these objections, the general consensus is that the archeological, cultural, genetic, and especially linguistic evidence all separately indicate varying degrees of shared ancestry among Austronesian-speaking peoples that justifies their treatment as a "phylogenetic unit".
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] This has led to the use of the term "Austronesian" in academic literature to refer not only to the Austronesian languages but also the Austronesian-speaking peoples, their societies, and the geographic area of Austronesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Some Austronesian-speaking groups are not direct descendants of Austronesians and acquired their languages through language shift, but this is believed to have happened only in a few instances, since the Austronesian expansion was too rapid for language shifts to have occurred fast enough.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In parts of Island Melanesia, migrations and paternal admixture from Papuan groups after the Austronesian expansion (estimated to have started at around 500 BCE) also resulted in gradual population turnover.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These secondary migrations were incremental and happened gradually enough that the culture and language of these groups remained Austronesian, even though in modern times, they are genetically more Papuan.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In the vast majority of cases, the language and material culture of Austronesian-speaking groups descend directly through generational continuity, especially in islands that were previously uninhabited.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Serious research into the Austronesian languages and its speakers has been ongoing since the 19th century.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Modern scholarship on Austronesian dispersion models is generally credited to two influential papers in the late 20th century: *The Colonization of the Pacific: A Genetic Trail* (Hill & Serjeantson, eds., 1989) and *The Austronesian Dispersal and the Origin of Languages* (Bellwood, 1991).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The topic is particularly interesting to scientists for the remarkably unique characteristics of the Austronesian speakers: their extent, diversity, and rapid dispersal.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Regardless, certain disagreements still exist among researchers with regards to chronology, origin, dispersal, adaptations to the island environments, interactions with preexisting populations in areas they settled, and cultural developments over time.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The mainstream accepted hypothesis is the "Out of Taiwan" model first proposed by Peter Bellwood.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] But there are multiple rival models that create a sort of "pseudo-competition" among their supporters due to narrow focus on data from limited geographic areas or disciplines.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The most notable of which is the "Out of Sundaland" (or "Out of Island Southeast Asia") model.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Austronesians were the first humans with seafaring vessels that could cross large distances on the open ocean; this technology allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Prior to the 16th-century colonial era, the Austronesian language family was the most widespread in the world, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Languages of the Austronesian family are today spoken by about 386 million people (4.9% of the global population), making it the fifth-largest language family by number of speakers.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Major Austronesian languages include Malay (around 250–270 million in Indonesia alone in its own literary standard, named Indonesian), Javanese, and Filipino (Tagalog).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The family contains 1,257 languages, the second-largest number of any language family.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The geographic region that encompasses native Austronesian-speaking populations is sometimes referred to as "Austronesia".
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In Indonesia, the nationalistic term Nusantara, from Old Javanese, is also popularly used for the Indonesian islands.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Austronesian regions are almost exclusively islands in the Pacific and Indian oceans, with predominantly tropical or subtropical climates with considerable seasonal rainfall.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Inhabitants of these regions include Taiwanese indigenous peoples, most ethnic groups in Brunei, East Timor, Indonesia, Madagascar, Malaysia, Micronesia, the Philippines, and Polynesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Also included are the Malays of Singapore; the Polynesians of New Zealand, Hawaii, and Chile; the Torres Strait Islanders of Australia; the non-Papuan peoples of Melanesia and coastal New Guinea; the Shibushi speakers of Mayotte, and the Malagasy and Shibushi speakers of Réunion.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Austronesians are also found in the regions of Southern Thailand; the Cham areas in Vietnam, Cambodia, and Hainan; and the Mergui Archipelago of Myanmar.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Additionally, modern-era migration has brought Austronesian-speaking people to the United States, Canada, Australia, the UK, mainland Europe, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, South Africa, Sri Lanka, Suriname, Hong Kong, Macau, and West Asian countries.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Some authors also propose further settlements and contacts in the past in areas that are not inhabited by Austronesian speakers today.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These range from likely hypotheses to very controversial claims with minimal evidence.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In 2009, Roger Blench compiled an expanded map of Austronesia that encompassed these claims based on a variety of evidence, such as historical accounts, loanwords, introduced plants and animals, genetics, archeological sites, and material culture.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They include areas like the Pacific coast of the Americas, Japan, the Yaeyama Islands, the Australian coast, Sri Lanka and coastal South Asia, the Persian Gulf, some Indian Ocean islands, East Africa, South Africa, and West Africa.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Austronesians also mixed with other preexisting populations as well as later migrant populations among the islands they settled, resulting in further genetic input.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The most notable are the Austroasiatic-speaking peoples in western Island Southeast Asia (peninsular Malaysia, Sumatra, Borneo, and Java); the Bantu peoples in Madagascar; as well as Japanese, Persian, Indian, Arab, and Han Chinese traders and migrants in more recent centuries.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Island Southeast Asia was settled by modern humans in the Paleolithic following coastal migration routes, presumably starting before 70,000 BP from Africa, long before the development of Austronesian cultures.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These populations are typified by having dark skin, curly hair, and short statures, leading Europeans to believe, in the 19th century, that they were related to African Pygmies.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] However, despite these physical similarities, genetic studies have shown that they are more closely related to other Eurasian populations than to Africans.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The lowered sea levels of the Pleistocene made some of the modern-day islands of Sundaland accessible via land bridges.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] However, the spread of humans across the Wallace line and into Sahul necessitated crossing bodies of water.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Remains of stone tools and marine shells in Liang Sarru, Salibabu Island, North Sulawesi, dated to 32,000–35,000 years ago, is possible evidence for the longest sea voyage by Paleolithic humans ever recorded.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The island was previously uninhabited by humans or hominins and can only be reached from either Mindanao or the Sangihe Islands by crossing an expanse of water at least 100 km (62 mi) wide, even during the low sea levels of the Pleistocene.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Other evidence of early maritime transport are the appearance of obsidian tools with the same source on neighboring islands.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These include the Philippine obsidian network (Mindoro and Palawan, ca.33,000-28,000 BP), and the Wallacea obsidian network (Timor, Atauro, Kisar, Alor, ca.22,000 BP).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] However, the method of crossing remains unknown and could have ranged from simple rafts to dugout canoes by the terminal Pleistocene.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These early settlers are generally historically referred to as "Australo-Melanesians", though the terminology is problematic, as they are genetically diverse, and most groups within Austronesia have significant Austronesian admixture and culture.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The unmixed descendants of these groups today include the interior Papuans and Indigenous Australians.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In modern literature, descendants of these groups, located in Island Southeast Asia west of Halmahera, are usually collectively referred to as "Negritos", while descendants of these groups east of Halmahera (excluding Indigenous Australians) are referred to as "Papuans".
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They can also be divided into two broad groups based on Denisovan admixture.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Philippine Negritos, Papuans, Melanesians, and Indigenous Australians display Denisovan admixture, while Malaysian and western Indonesian Negritos (Orang Asli) and Andamanese islanders do not.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Mahdi (2017) also uses the term "Qata" (from Proto-Malayo-Polynesian *qata) to distinguish the indigenous populations of Southeast Asia, versus "Tau" (from Proto-Austronesian *Cau) for the later settlers from Taiwan and mainland China.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Both are based on proto-forms for the word "person" in Malayo-Polynesian languages that referred to darker-skinned and lighter-skinned groups, respectively.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Jinam *et al.* (2017) also proposed the term "First Sundaland People" in place of "Negrito", as a more accurate name for the original population of Southeast Asia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These populations are genetically distinct from later Austronesians, but through fairly extensive population admixture, most modern Austronesians have varying levels of ancestry from these groups.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The same is true for some populations historically considered "non-Austronesians", due to physical differences—like Philippine Negritos, Orang Asli, and Austronesian-speaking Melanesians, all of whom have Austronesian admixture.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In Polynesians in Remote Oceania, for example, the admixture is around 20 to 30% Papuan and 70 to 80% Austronesian.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The Melanesians in Near Oceania are roughly around 20% Austronesian and 80% Papuan, while in the natives of the Lesser Sunda Islands, the admixture is around 50% Austronesian and 50% Papuan.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Similarly, in the Philippines, the groups traditionally considered to be "Negrito" vary between 30 and 50% Austronesian.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The high degree of assimilation among Austronesian, Negrito, and Papuan groups indicates that the Austronesian expansion was largely peaceful.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Rather than violent displacement, the settlers and the indigenous groups absorbed each other.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] It is believed that in some cases, like in the Toalean culture of Sulawesi (c.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] 8,000–1,500 BP), it is even more accurate to say that the densely populated indigenous hunter-gatherer groups absorbed the incoming Austronesian farmers, rather than the other way around.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Mahdi (2016) further asserts that Proto-Malayo-Polynesian *tau-mata ("person") is derived from a composite protoform *Cau ma-qata, combining "Tau" and "Qata" and indicative of the mixing of the two ancestral population types in these regions.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The broad consensus on the Urheimat (homeland) of Austronesian languages as well as the Neolithic early Austronesian peoples is accepted to be Taiwan, as well as the Penghu Islands.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They are believed to have descended from ancestral populations in coastal mainland southern China, which are generally referred to as the "pre‑Austronesians".
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Through these pre-Austronesians, Austronesians may also share a common ancestry with neighboring groups in Neolithic southern China.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These Neolithic pre-Austronesians from the coast of southeastern China are believed to have migrated to Taiwan between approximately 10,000 and 6000 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Other research has suggested that, according to radiocarbon dates, Austronesians may have migrated from mainland China to Taiwan as late as 4000 BCE (Dapenkeng culture).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They continued to maintain regular contact with the mainland until 1500 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The identity of the Neolithic pre-Austronesian cultures in China is contentious.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Tracing Austronesian prehistory in Fujian and Taiwan has been difficult due to the southward expansion of the Han dynasty (2nd century BCE) and the recent Qing dynasty annexation of Taiwan (1683 CE).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Today, the only Austronesian language in southern China is Tsat, spoken in Hainan.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The politicization of archaeology is also problematic, particularly erroneous reconstructions among some Chinese archaeologists of non-Sinitic sites as Han.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Some authors, favoring the "Out of Sundaland" model, like William Meacham, reject the southern Chinese mainland origin of pre-Austronesians entirely.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Nevertheless, based on linguistic, archaeological, and genetic evidence, Austronesians are most strongly associated with the early farming cultures of the Yangtze River basin that domesticated rice from around 13,500 to 8,200 BP.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They display typical Austronesian technological hallmarks, including tooth removal, teeth blackening, jade carving, tattooing, stilt houses, advanced boatbuilding, aquaculture, wetland agriculture, and the domestication of dogs, pigs, and chickens.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These include the Kuahuqiao, Hemudu, Majiabang, Songze, Liangzhu, and Dapenkeng cultures that occupied the coastal regions between the Yangtze River delta and the Min River delta.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Based on linguistic evidence, there have been proposals linking Austronesians with other linguistic families into linguistic macrofamilies that are relevant to the identity of the pre-Austronesian populations.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The most notable are the connections of Austronesians to the neighboring Austroasiatic, Kra-Dai, and Sinitic peoples (as Austric, Austro-Tai, and Sino-Austronesian, respectively).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These are still not widely accepted, as evidence of these relationships are still tenuous, and the methods used are highly contentious.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Under that view, there was an east–west genetic alignment, resulting from a rice-based population expansion, in the southern part of East Asia: Austroasiatic-Kra-Dai-Austronesian, with unrelated Sino-Tibetan occupying a more northerly tier.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Depending on the author, other hypotheses have also included other language families like Hmong–Mien and even Japanese-Ryukyuan into the larger Austric hypothesis.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These peoples were assimilated linguistically and culturally by incoming Austronesian peoples in what is now modern-day Indonesia and Malaysia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They propose that the distinctiveness of Kra-Dai (it is tonal and monosyllabic) was the result of linguistic restructuring due to contact with Hmong–Mien and Sinitic cultures.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Aside from linguistic evidence, Roger Blench has also noted cultural similarities between the two groups, like facial tattooing, tooth removal or ablation, teeth blackening, snake (or dragon) cults, and the multiple-tongued jaw harps shared by the indigenous Taiwanese and Kra-Dai-speakers.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] However, archaeological evidence for this is still sparse.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] This is believed to be similar to what happened to the Cham people, who were originally Austronesian settlers (likely from Borneo) to southern Vietnam around 2100–1900 BP and had languages similar to Malay.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Their languages underwent several restructuring events to syntax and phonology due to contact with the nearby tonal languages of Mainland Southeast Asia and Hainan.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Although the populations of the Malay peninsula, Sumatra, Java, and neighboring islands are Austronesian-speaking, they have significantly high admixture from Mainland Southeast Asian populations.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These areas were already populated (most probably by speakers of Austroasiatic languages) before they were reached by the Austronesian expansion, roughly 3,000 years ago.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Currently, only the indigenous Aslians still speak Austroasiatic languages.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] However, some of the languages in the region show signs of underlying Austroasiatic substrates.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] According to Juha Janhunen and Ann Kumar, Austronesians may have also settled parts of southern Japan, especially on the islands of Kyushu and Shikoku, and influenced or created the Japanese hierarchical society.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] It is suggested that Japanese tribes like the Hayato people, the Kumaso, and the Azumi were of Austronesian origin.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Until today, local traditions and festivals show similarities to Malayo-Polynesian culture.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The Sino-Austronesian hypothesis, on the other hand, is a relatively new hypothesis by Laurent Sagart, first proposed in 1990.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] It argues for a north–south linguistic genetic relationship between Chinese and Austronesian.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] This is based on sound correspondences in basic vocabulary and morphological parallels.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Sagart places special significance in shared vocabulary on cereal crops, citing them as evidence of shared linguistic origin.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] However, this has largely been rejected by other linguists.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] This corresponded with the widespread introduction of rice cultivation to Proto-Sinitic speakers and conversely, millet cultivation to Pre-Austronesians.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] An Austronesian substratum in formerly Austronesian territories that have been Sinicized after the Iron Age Han expansion is also another explanation for the correspondences that do not require a genetic relationship.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The surviving Austronesian populations in Taiwan should rather be considered as the result of various Neolithic migration waves from the mainland and back-migration from the Philippines.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These incoming migrants almost certainly spoke languages related to Austronesian or pre-Austronesian, although their phonology and grammar would have been quite diverse.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Blench considers the Austronesians in Taiwan to have been a melting pot of immigrants from various parts of the coast of East China that had been migrating to Taiwan by 4000 BP.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Based on geography and cultural vocabulary, Blench believes that the Yuanshan people may have spoken Northeast Formosan languages.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Thus, Blench believes that there is in fact no "apical" ancestor of Austronesian in the sense that there was no true single Proto-Austronesian language that gave rise to present-day Austronesian languages.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Instead, multiple migrations of various pre-Austronesian peoples and languages from the Chinese mainland that were related but distinct came together to form what we now know as Austronesian in Taiwan.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Hence, Blench considers the single-migration model into Taiwan by pre-Austronesians to be inconsistent with both the archaeological and linguistic (lexical) evidence.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The **Austronesian expansion** (also called the "Out of Taiwan" model) is a large-scale migration of Austronesians from Taiwan, occurring around 3000 to 1500 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Population growth primarily fueled this migration.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] These first settlers settled in northern Luzon, in the archipelago of the Philippines, intermingling with the earlier Australo-Melanesian population who had inhabited the islands since about 23,000 years earlier.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Over the next thousand years, Austronesian peoples migrated southeast to the rest of the Philippines, and into the islands of the Celebes Sea and Borneo.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] From southwestern Borneo, Austronesians spread further west in a single migration event to both Sumatra and the coastal regions of southern Vietnam, becoming the ancestors of the speakers of the Malayic and Chamic branches of the Austronesian language family.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] A 2021 study, however, suggests an earlier divergence date between Cordilleran-related groups and populations from mainland East Asia and Taiwan at ~8,000 B.P., coinciding with the Cordilleran settlement of the Philippines.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Soon after reaching the Philippines, Austronesians colonized the Northern Mariana Islands by 1500 BCE or even earlier, becoming the first humans to reach Remote Oceania.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The Chamorro migration was also unique in that it was the only Austronesian migration to the Pacific Islands to successfully retain rice cultivation.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Palau and Yap were settled by separate voyages by 1000 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Another important migration branch was by the Lapita culture, which rapidly spread into the islands off the coast of northern New Guinea and into the Solomon Islands and other parts of coastal New Guinea and Island Melanesia by 1200 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They reached the islands of Fiji, Samoa, and Tonga by around 900 to 800 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] This remained the furthest extent of the Austronesian expansion into Polynesia until around 700 CE, when there was another surge of island colonization.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] It reached the Cook Islands, Tahiti, and the Marquesas by 700 CE; Hawaii by 900 CE; Rapa Nui by 1000 CE; and New Zealand by 1200 CE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] For a few centuries, the Polynesian islands were connected by bidirectional long-distance sailing, with the exception of Rapa Nui, which had limited further contact due to its isolated geographical location.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Island groups like the Pitcairns, the Kermadec Islands, and the Norfolk Islands were also formerly settled by Austronesians but later abandoned.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] There is also putative evidence, based in the spread of the sweet potato, that Austronesians may have reached South America from Polynesia, where they might have traded with the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] In the Indian Ocean, Austronesians in Maritime Southeast Asia established trade links with South Asia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] They also established early long-distance contacts with Africa, possibly as early as before 500 BCE, based on archaeological evidence like banana phytoliths in Cameroon and Uganda and remains of Neolithic chicken bones in Zanzibar.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] By the end of the first millennium BCE, Austronesians were already sailing maritime trade routes linking the Han dynasty of China with the western Indian Ocean trade in India, the Roman Empire, and Africa.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] An Austronesian group, originally from the Makassar Strait region around Kalimantan and Sulawesi, eventually settled Madagascar, either directly from Southeast Asia or from preexisting mixed Austronesian-Bantu populations from East Africa.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Estimates for when this occurred vary, from the 5th to 7th centuries CE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] It is likely that the Austronesians that settled Madagascar followed a coastal route through South Asia and East Africa, rather than directly across the Indian Ocean.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Genetic evidence suggests that some individuals of Austronesian descent reached Africa and the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] A competing hypothesis to the "Out of Taiwan" model is the "Out of Sundaland" hypothesis, favored by a minority of authors.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Notable proponents include William Meacham, Stephen Oppenheimer, and Wilhelm Solheim.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] For various reasons, they have proposed that the homelands of Austronesians were within Island Southeast Asia (ISEA), particularly in the Sundaland landmass drowned during the end of the Last Glacial Period by rising sea levels.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Proponents of these hypotheses point to the ancient origins of mtDNA in Southeast Asian populations, pre-dating the Austronesian expansion, as proof that Austronesians originated from within Island Southeast Asia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] However, these have been repudiated by studies using whole genome sequencing, which have found that all ISEA populations had genes originating from aboriginal Taiwanese.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Contrary to the claim of a south-to-north migration in the "Out of Sundaland" hypothesis, the new whole genome analysis strongly confirms the north-to-south dispersal of the Austronesian peoples in the prevailing "Out of Taiwan" hypothesis.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Researchers have further pointed out that while humans have been living in Sundaland for at least 40,000 years, the Austronesian people were recent arrivals.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The results of the previous studies failed to take into account admixture with the more ancient but unrelated Negrito and Papuan populations.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] By the beginning of the first millennium CE, most of the Austronesian inhabitants in Maritime Southeast Asia began trading with India and China.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The adoption of the Hindu statecraft model allowed the creation of Indianized kingdoms, such as Tarumanagara, Champa, Butuan, Langkasuka, Melayu, Srivijaya, Mataram, Majapahit, and Bali.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Between the 5th and the 15th century, Hinduism and Buddhism were established as the main religion in the region.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Muslim traders from the Arabian Peninsula were thought to have brought Islam by the 10th century.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] This was established as the dominant religion in the Malay archipelago by the 16th century.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The Austronesian inhabitants of Near Oceania and Remote Oceania were unaffected by this cultural trade and retained their indigenous culture in the Pacific region.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The Kingdom of Larantuka in Flores, East Nusa Tenggara, was the only Christian (Roman Catholic) indigenous kingdom in Indonesia and in Southeast Asia, with its first king named Lorenzo.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] Meanwhile, the British, Germans, French, Americans, and Japanese began establishing spheres of influence within the Pacific islands during the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The Japanese later invaded most of Southeast Asia and some parts of the Pacific during World War II.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p01] The latter half of the 20th century initiated independence of modern-day Indonesia, Malaysia, East Timor, and many of the Pacific island nations, as well as the re-independence of the Philippines.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The native culture of Austronesia varies from region to region.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The early Austronesian peoples considered the sea as the basic feature of their life.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Following their diaspora to Southeast Asia and Oceania, they migrated by boat to other islands.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Boats of different sizes and shapes have been found in every Austronesian culture, from Madagascar, Maritime Southeast Asia, to Polynesia, and have different names.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In Southeast Asia, head-hunting was restricted to the highlands as a result of warfare.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Mummification is only found among the highland Austronesian Filipinos and in some Indonesian groups in Celebes and Borneo.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Seagoing catamaran and outrigger ship technologies were the most important innovations of the Austronesian peoples.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They were the first humans with vessels capable of crossing vast distances of water.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The crossing from the Philippines to the Mariana Islands at around 1500 BCE, a distance of more than 2,500 km (1,600 mi), is likely the world's first and longest ocean crossing of that time.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] These maritime technologies enabled them to colonize the Indo-Pacific in prehistoric times.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Austronesian groups continue to be the primary users of outrigger canoes today.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Early researchers like Heine-Geldern (1932) and Hornell (1943) once believed that catamarans evolved from outrigger canoes, but modern authors specializing in Austronesian cultures, like Doran (1981) and Mahdi (1988), now believe it to be the opposite.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Two canoes bound together developed directly from minimal raft technologies of two logs tied together.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Over time, the double-hulled canoe form developed into the asymmetric double canoe, where one hull is smaller than the other.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Eventually the smaller hull became the prototype outrigger, giving way to the single outrigger canoe, then to the reversible single outrigger canoe.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Finally, the single outrigger types developed into the double outrigger canoe (or trimarans).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] This would also explain why older Austronesian populations in Island Southeast Asia tend to favor double outrigger canoes, as it keeps the boats stable when tacking.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] However, there are small regions where catamarans and single-outrigger canoes are still used.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In contrast, more distant outlying descendant populations in Micronesia, Polynesia and Madagascar retained the double-hull and the single-outrigger canoe types, but the technology for double outriggers never reached them (although it exists in western Melanesia).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] To deal with the problem of the boat's instability when the outrigger faces leeward when tacking, they instead developed the shunting technique in sailing, in conjunction with reversible single-outriggers.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The simplest form of all ancestral Austronesian boats had five parts.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The bottom consisted of a single piece of hollowed-out log.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] At the sides were two planks, and two horseshoe-shaped wood pieces formed the prow and stern.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] These were fitted tightly together edge-to-edge, with dowels inserted into holes in between, and then lashed to each other with ropes (made from rattan or fiber) wrapped around protruding lugs on the planks.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] This characteristic and ancient Austronesian boatbuilding practice is known as the "lashed-lug" technique.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They were commonly caulked with pastes made from various plants as well as tapa bark and fibers that would expand when wet, further tightening joints and making the hull watertight.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They formed the shell of the boat, which was then reinforced by horizontal ribs.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Shipwrecks of Austronesian ships can be identified from this construction as well as the absence of metal nails.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Austronesian ships traditionally had no central rudders but were instead steered using an oar on one side.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The ancestral rig was the mastless triangular crab claw sail, which had two booms that could be tilted to the wind.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] These were built in the double-canoe configuration or had a single outrigger on the windward side.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In Island Southeast Asia, these developed into double outriggers on each side, which provided greater stability.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The triangular crab claw sails also later developed into square or rectangular tanja sails, which, like crab claw sails, had distinctive booms spanning the upper and lower edges.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Fixed masts also developed later in both Southeast Asia (usually as bipod or tripod masts) and Oceania.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Austronesians traditionally made their sails from woven mats of the resilient and salt-resistant pandanus leaves.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] These sails allowed them to embark on long-distance voyaging.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In some cases, however, they were one-way voyages.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The motives of early Rapa Nui natives and Māori to establish their settlements (Easter Island and New Zealand) are believed to have isolated their settlements from the rest of Polynesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The ancient Champa of Vietnam also uniquely developed basket-hulled boats whose hulls were composed of woven and resin-caulked bamboo, either entirely or in conjunction with plank strakes.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They ranged from small coracles (*o thúng*) to large oceangoing trading ships like the *ghe mành*.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The acquisition of catamaran and outrigger technology by non-Austronesian peoples in Sri Lanka and southern India is due to the result of very early Austronesian contact with the region, including the Maldives and the Laccadive Islands, estimated to have occurred around 1000 to 600 BCE and onwards.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] This may have possibly included limited colonization by people who have since been assimilated.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] This is still evident in Sri Lankan and South Indian languages.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Austronesian architecture is diverse but often shares certain characteristics that indicate a common origin.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Austronesian structures commonly have raised floors.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The structures are raised on piles, usually with space underneath also utilized for storage or domestic animals.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The raised design has multiple advantages, including mitigating damage during flooding and (in very tall examples) acting as defensive structures during conflicts.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The house posts are also distinctively capped with larger-diameter discs at the top, to prevent vermin and pests from entering the structures by climbing them.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Austronesian houses and other structures are usually built in wetlands and alongside bodies of water but can also be constructed in the highlands or even directly on shallow water.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Building structures on pilings is believed to be derived from the design of raised granaries and storehouses, which are highly important status symbols among the ancestrally rice-cultivating Austronesians.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The rice granary shrine was also the archetypal religious building among Austronesian cultures and was used to store carvings of ancestor spirits and local deities.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Another common feature are pitched roofs with ornamented gables.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The most notable of these are saddlebacked roofs, a design common for longhouses used for village meetings or ceremonies.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The overall effect of this is reminiscent of a boat, underlining the strong maritime connections of Austronesian cultures.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The boat motif is common throughout, particularly in Eastern Indonesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In some ethnic groups, the houses are built on platforms that resemble catamarans.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Among the Nage people, a woven representation of a boat is added to the ridge of the roof; among the Manggarai people, the roofs of houses are shaped like an upside-down boat; while among the people of Tanimbar and eastern Flores, the ridge itself is carved into a representation of a boat.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Furthermore, elements of Austronesian structures (as well as society in general) are often referred to in terminologies used for boats and sailing.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] These include calling elements of structures "masts", "sails", or "rudders", or calling the village leaders "captains" or "steersmen".
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In the case of the Philippines, the villages themselves are referred to as *barangay*, from an alternate form of *balangay*, a type of sailboat used for trading and colonization.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Austronesian buildings have spiritual significance, often containing what has been coined by anthropologist James J.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] These are specific posts, beams, platforms, altars, and so on that embody the house as a whole, usually consecrated at the time of building.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The Austronesian house itself also often symbolizes various aspects of indigenous Austronesian cosmology and animism.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In the majority of cases, the loft of the house (usually placed above the hearth), is considered to be the domain of deities and spirits.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] It is essentially a raised granary built into the structure of the house itself and functioning as a second floor.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] It is commonly used to store sacred objects (like effigies of granary idols or deceased ancestors), heirlooms, and other important objects.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] These areas are usually not part of the regular living space and may only be accessible to certain members of the family or after performing a specific ritual.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Other parts of the house may also be associated with certain deities, and thus certain activities like receiving guests or conducting marriage ceremonies can only be performed in specific areas.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] While rice cultivation wasn't among the technologies carried into Remote Oceania, raised storehouses still survived.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The *pātaka* of the Māori people is an example.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The largest *pātaka* are elaborately adorned with carvings and are often the tallest buildings in the Māori *pā*.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] These were used to store implements, weapons, ships, and other valuables; while smaller *pātaka* were used to store provisions.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] A special type of *pātaka*, supported by a single tall post, also had ritual importance and was used to isolate high-born children during their training for leadership.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The majority of Austronesian structures are not permanent.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They are made from perishable materials like wood, bamboo, plant fiber, and leaves.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Similar to traditional Austronesian boats, they do not use nails but are traditionally constructed solely by joints, weaving, ties, and dowels.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Elements of the structures are repaired and replaced regularly or as they get damaged.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Because of this, archaeological records of prehistoric Austronesian structures are usually limited to traces of house posts, with no way of determining the original building plans.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Indirect evidence of traditional Austronesian architecture, however, can be gleaned from their contemporary representations in art, such as friezes on the walls of later Hindu-Buddhist stone temples (like in reliefs at Borobudur and Prambanan).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] But these are limited to the recent centuries.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They can also be reconstructed linguistically from shared terms for architectural elements, like ridge poles, thatch, rafters, house posts, hearths, notched log ladders, storage racks, public buildings, and so on.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Linguistic evidence also makes it clear that stilt houses were already present among Austronesian groups since at least the Late Neolithic.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In modern Indonesia, varying styles are collectively known as *rumah adat*.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Arbi *et al.* (2013) have also noted the striking similarities between Austronesian architecture and Japanese traditional raised architecture (*shinmei-zukuri*).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Particularly the buildings of the Ise Grand Shrine, which contrast with the pit-houses typical of the Neolithic Yayoi period.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They propose significant Neolithic contact between the people of southern Japan and Austronesians or pre-Austronesians that occurred prior to the spread of Han Chinese cultural influence to the islands.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Rice cultivation is also believed to have been introduced to Japan from a para-Austronesian group from coastal eastern China.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Waterson (2009) has also argued that the architectural tradition of stilt houses is originally Austronesian and that similar building traditions in Japan and mainland Asia (notably among Kra-Dai and Austroasiatic-speaking groups) correspond to contacts with a prehistoric Austronesian network.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Outside of Taiwan, assemblages of red-slipped pottery, plainware, and incised and stamped pottery associated with Austronesian migrations are first documented from around 2000 to 1800 BCE in the northern Philippines, from sites in the Batanes Islands and the Cagayan Valley of Northern Luzon.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] From there, pottery technology rapidly spread to the east, south, and southwest.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] This type of pottery dispersed south and southwest to the rest of Island Southeast Asia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The eastward and southward branches of the migrations converged in Island Melanesia, resulting in what is now known as the Lapita culture, centered around the Bismarck Archipelago.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The oldest known pottery assemblages in Oceania are circle- and punctate/dentate-stamped pottery in the Marianas Islands, securely dated to 1500 BCE–1300 BCE from multiple archaeological sites.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] It predates the earliest Lapita culture pottery assemblages (c.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] 1350 –1300 BCE) and bears closest resemblance to a subset of the more diverse Nagsabaran pottery of the northern Philippines.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] It is currently disputed whether this is indicative of a direct ancient voyage from the northern Philippines to the Marianas.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Hung *et al.* (2011) proposed a direct deliberate voyage from eastern Luzon, which would make it the longest sea crossing undertaken by that time in human history.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] This has also been proposed by earlier authors like Blust (2000) and Reid (2002), based on linguistics.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Winter *et al.* (2012), on the other hand, dismissed the similarities as being generic rather than specific to the region.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] This is from both analysis of the microscopic structure of the shards (indicating manufacturing techniques) and the impossibility of drift voyaging from Luzon, due to the prevailing wind and currents.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Instead of a voyage directly from Luzon, they instead proposed an origin either from a direct single voyage from Mindanao (southern Philippines) or Morotai (Maluku Islands) to Guam; or two voyages, with way stations in Palau or Yap.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Hung *et al.* (2012) pointed out in response that no pottery assemblages older than 2,000 years old have been found in Morotai, which also has a Papuan-speaking population.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They also mentioned that present-day data on wind and currents is not a reliable way of ascertaining migration routes, and that the voyages settling Remote Oceania would have been deliberate, not uncontrolled drifting.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Similar presumptions by Thor Heyerdahl led to his erroneous conclusion that Polynesia was settled from the Americas.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Pottery manufacturing techniques are also diverse, even within a single community.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Thus, analysis of manufacturing methods is less significant than comparison of decorative systems.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Nevertheless, Hung *et al.* (2012) emphasized that they also did not discount other sources (yet undiscovered) from the southern Philippines.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They also proposed the Eastern Visayas as a likely point of origin.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Sources south of the Philippines remain unlikely without further archaeological findings due to their related pottery assemblages being younger than 1500 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The dentate-stamped pottery of the Lapita culture (c.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] 1350–1300 BCE) retained elements also found in the Nagsabaran pottery in the Philippines, including stamped circles as well as the cross-in-circle motif.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They carried pottery technology as far as Tonga in Polynesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Pottery technology in Tonga, however, became reduced to undecorated plainware within only two centuries before abruptly disappearing completely by around 400 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Pottery was absent in subsequent migrations to the rest of Remote Oceania, being replaced instead with carved wooden or bamboo containers, bottle gourds, and baskets.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] However, the geometric designs and stylized figures used in the pottery are still present in other surviving art forms, such as tattooing, weaving, and barkcloth patterns.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] A common practice among Austronesians in a large area of Island Southeast Asia is the use of burial jars, which emerged during the Late Neolithic and flourished in the first millennium CE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They are characteristic of a region bordered by the Philippines to the north, southern Sumatra in the southwest, and Sumba and the Maluku Islands in the southeast.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] However, these didn't comprise a single tradition but can be grouped into at least fourteen different traditions scattered across the islands.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In most cases, the earliest burial jars used were large indigenous earthenware jars, followed by indigenous or imported stoneware jars (*martaban*), and finally imported porcelain jars acquired from the burgeoning maritime trade with China and Mainland Southeast Asia around the 14th century CE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Slit drums are indigenous Austronesian musical instruments invented and used by Southeast Asian-Austronesian and Oceanic-Austronesian ethnic groups.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Gong ensembles are also a common musical heritage of Island Southeast Asia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The casting of gong instruments is believed to have originated from the Bronze Age cultures of Mainland Southeast Asia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] It spread to the Austronesian islands initially through trade as prestige goods.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] However, mainland Asian gongs were never used in ensembles; the innovation of using gong sets is uniquely Austronesian.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Gong ensembles are found in western Malayo-Polynesian groups, though they never penetrated much further east.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] There are roughly two gong ensemble traditions among Austronesians, which also produced gongs in ancient times.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In western Island Southeast Asia, these traditions are collectively known as *gamelan*, being centred on the island of Java in Indonesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They include the *celempung* of the Malay Peninsula, *talempung* of northern Sumatra, *caklempung* of central Sumatra, *chalempung* of southern Sumatra, *bonang* of Java, *kromong* of western Kalimantan, *engkromong* of Sarawak, and *trompong* of western Nusa Tenggara.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In eastern Island Southeast Asia, these traditions are known as *kulintang* and are centred in Mindanao and the Sulu archipelago of the southern Philippines.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They include the *kulintangan* of Sabah and Palawan, *kolintang* of northern Sulawesi, *kulintang* of Halmahera and Timor, and *totobuang* of the southern Maluku Islands.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] The ancestral pre-Austronesian Liangzhu culture (3400–2250 BCE) of the Yangtze River delta was one of the ancient centers of Neolithic jade carving.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Jade was spread to Taiwan by around 3,000 BCE, then further into the Philippines at 2,000 BCE and Vietnam at 1,800–1,500 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] All of them began to produce various tools and ornaments in indigenous jade workshops, including adzes, bracelets, beads, and rings.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] These typically depicted two-headed animals or were ring-shaped with side projections.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They were indicative of a very active ancient maritime trading region, known as the Sa Huynh-Kalanay Interaction Sphere, that imported and exported raw jade and finished jade ornaments.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] They were produced during a period from 500 BCE to as late as 1000 CE, although later examples were replaced with metal, wood, bone, clay, green mica, black nephrite, or shell materials, rather than green jade.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Polished and ground stone adzes, gouges, and other implements, some of which are made from jade-like stone, have also been recorded in areas of Island Melanesia and eastern New Guinea associated with the Lapita culture.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] These were considered valuable currency and were primarily used to trade for goods.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] In 2012, a Lapita jadeite gouge used for wood carving was found on Emirau Island in the Bismarck Archipelago.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] It was dated to around 3,300 BCE, but the origin of the jade material is unknown.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p02] Similar stone tools have also been found in New Caledonia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Jade was absent in most of Remote Oceania, due to the lack of deposits.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] However, there is putative evidence that Polynesians may have remained familiar with jade and may acquired it through prehistoric trade contacts with New Caledonia, Island Melanesia, and/or New Zealand.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Jade-carving traditions reappeared among the Māori people of New Zealand.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] These were produced from locally sourced *pounamu* (greenstone) and were used to produce *taonga* (treasure).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They include various tools and weapons like adzes, scrapers, fishing hooks, and *mere*, as well as ornaments like the *hei-tiki* and *hei matau*.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Certain ornaments like the *pekapeka* (double-headed animal pendant) and the *kākā pōria* (bird leg ring) bear remarkably strong resemblances to the double-headed and ring-type *lingling‑o*.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] There are approximately six to seven hundred rock art sites discovered in Southeast Asia and Island Melanesia, as well as over eight hundred megalithic sites.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The sites specifically associated with the Austronesian expansion contain examples of indigenous pictograms and petroglyphs.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Despite proximity, these traditions can be distinguished readily from the Australo-Melanesian rock art traditions of Australia (except the Torres Strait Islands) as well as the interior highlands of New Guinea, indicating the borders of the extent of the Austronesian expansion.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Dating rock art is difficult, but some of the sites subjected to direct dating pre-date Austronesian arrival, like the Lene Hara paintings of East Timor, which have an age range of 6,300 to 26,000 BP.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Conversely, others are more recent and can be dated indirectly by their subjects.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The depictions of pottery, ships, and metal objects, for example, put certain rock art sites at a range of 2,000 to 4,000 BP.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Some hunter-gatherer groups have also continued to produce rock art well into the present period, as evidenced by their modern subjects.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The Megalithic Culture is mostly limited to western Island Southeast Asia, with the greatest concentration being western Indonesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] While most sites are not dated, the age ranges of dating sites are between the 2nd and 16th centuries CE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Prasetyo (2006) suggests that the megalithic traditions are not originally Austronesian but rather innovations acquired through trade with India and China, but this has little to no evidence in the intervening regions in Thailand, Vietnam, and the Philippines.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The Austronesian Painting Traditions are the most common types of rock art in Island Southeast Asia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They consist of scenes and pictograms typically found in rock shelters and caves near coastal areas.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They are characteristically rendered in red ocher pigments for the earlier forms, later sometimes superseded by paintings done in black charcoal pigments.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Their sites are mostly clustered in Eastern Indonesia and Island Melanesia, although a few examples can be found in the rest of Island Southeast Asia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Their occurrence has a high correlation to Austronesian-speaking areas, further evidenced by the appearance of bronze artifacts in the paintings.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They are mostly found near the coastlines.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Their common motifs include hand stencils, "sun-ray" designs, boats, and active human figures with headdresses or weapons and other paraphernalia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They also feature geometric motifs similar to those of the Austronesian Engraving Style.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Some paintings are also associated with traces of human burials and funerary rites, including ship burials.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The representations of boats themselves are believed to be connected to the widespread "ship of the dead" Austronesian funerary practices.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The earliest APT site dated is from Vanuatu and was found to be around 3,000 BP, corresponding to the initial migration wave of the Austronesians.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] These early sites are largely characterized by face motifs and hand stencils.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Later sites, from 1,500 BP onwards, however, begin to show regional divergence in their art styles.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] APT can be readily distinguished from older Pleistocene-era Australo-Melanesian cave paintings by their motifs, color, and composition, though they can often be found in the same locality.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The most recognizable motifs of APT (like boats) do not occur in cave paintings (or engravings) that definitely pre-date the Austronesian arrival—the sole exception being the stenciled hand motif.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Some APT examples are also characteristically found in relatively inaccessible locations, including very high up in cliffsides overlooking the sea.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] No traces of APT have been found in Taiwan or the Philippines, though there is continuity in the motifs of spirals and concentric circles found in ancestral petroglyphs.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] AES, which consists of petroglyphs carved into rock surfaces, is far less common than APT.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The majority of these sites are in coastal New Guinea and Island Melanesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] AES sites, which can be tentatively traced back to the similar Wanshan petroglyphs of Taiwan, are believed to be largely correlated to the prehistoric extent of the Lapita culture.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The common motif of this tradition is curvilinear geometric engravings like spirals, concentric circles, and face-like forms.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] These resemble the geometric motifs in APT, though they are considered to be two separate artistic traditions.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] AES is particularly dominant in the Solomon Islands and New Caledonia, where engravings are far more abundant than painted sites.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] O'Connor *et al.* (2015) proposes that APT developed during the initial rapid southward Austronesian expansion, and not before, possibly as a response to the communication challenges brought about by the new maritime mode of living.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The easternmost islands of Island Melanesia (Vanuatu, Fiji, and New Caledonia) are considered part of Remote Oceania, as they are beyond the inter-island visibility threshold.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] These island groups begin to show divergence from the APT and AES traditions of Near Oceania.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] While their art traditions show a clear continuation of the APT and AES traditions, they also feature innovations unique to each island group, like the increasing use of black charcoal, rectilinear motifs, and being more commonly found inside sacred caves rather than on open cliffsides.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In Micronesia, the rock art traditions can be divided into three general regions: western, central, and eastern.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In western Micronesia (Palau, Yap, Guam, and the Northern Mariana Islands), rock art primarily consists of paintings on high cave ceilings and sea-facing cliffs.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] It is very similar to APT in terms of its motifs as well as its placement in relatively inaccessible locations.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Common motifs include hand stencils, faces, turtles and fish, concentric circles, and characteristic four-pointed stars.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Petroglyphs are rare and mainly consist of human forms with triangular bodies without heads or arms.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] This is believed to be connected to the funerary rite of removing the heads from the bodies of deceased relatives.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] A notable megalithic tradition in western Micronesia are the *haligi* stone pillars of the Chamorro people.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] These are capped stone pillars that are believed to have served as supports for raised buildings.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They are associated with the Latte period (900 to 1700 CE), when a new wave of migrants from Southeast Asia reintroduced rice cultivation to the islands.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Another megalithic tradition is that of the rai stones, massive doughnut-shaped discs of rock that were used as currency on Yap.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Rock art in central Micronesia (Chuuk, Pohnpei, and Kosrae), in contrast, is dominated by rock engravings with motifs tying it to the rock art traditions of Island Melanesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They include curvilinear shapes like spirals and concentric circles, tree-like shapes, and the distinctive "enveloped cross" motif.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The Pohnpaid petroglyphs are the largest assemblage of rock engravings in the region, with motifs dominated by footprints, enveloped crosses, and outlined "sword-paddles".
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Central Micronesia also hosts the ruins of the stone cities of Nan Madol (1,180–1,200 CE) and Leluh (1,200–1,800 CE), on the islands of Pohnpei and Kosrae, respectively.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In the low-lying atolls of eastern Micronesia, rock art is rare-to-nonexistent, due to the absence of suitable rock surfaces for painting or engraving.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In Polynesia, rock art is dominated by petroglyphs, rather than paintings, and they show less variation than the rock art of Near Oceania and ISEA.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In the western Polynesian islands nearest to Island Melanesia, rock art is rare (like in Tonga and Samoa) or absent entirely (like in the Cook Islands).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] However, petroglyphs are abundant on the islands in the further reaches of the Polynesian triangle, particularly on Hawaii, the Marquesas, and Rapa Nui.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Rapa Nui has the densest concentration of engravings in Polynesia as a whole, while the Puʻuloa petroglyphs site on Hawaii has the largest number of petroglyphs in a single site, at over 21,000 engravings.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Polynesia also features megalithic sacred ceremonial centers generally known as *marae*.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] On Tonga and Samoa, the existing rock art sites consist mostly of engravings with motifs including curvilinear shapes, human figures, "jellyfish", turtles, birds, and footprints.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] These are typically carved in natural rock formations or *marae* sites.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In the central-eastern Polynesian islands, which include the Marquesas and the Society Islands, petroglyphs are more numerous.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They show the archetypal Polynesian motifs of turtles, faces, cup-like depressions (cupules), stick-like human figures, boats, fish, curvilinear shapes, and concentric circles.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Like in western Polynesia, they are typically carved into *marae* sites or in rocks beside streams.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The existing rock paintings also display the same motifs but are rendered in different styles.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] On the Hawaiian islands, the abundant petroglyphs are remarkably all similar in execution.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Their common subjects include stick-like human figures, dogs, boats, sails, paddles, footprints, and ceremonial headdresses.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Depictions of marine life, however, are rare, unlike in the rest of Polynesia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They are typically carved into boulders, lava rock formations, and cliffsides.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Red paintings of dogs on cliffsides and caves can also be found on Kauʻai and Maui.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The megalithic traditions of Hawaii can be exemplified by the *heiau* sacred sites, which can range from simple earth terraces to standing stones.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] On Rapa Nui, the engravings are distinctive but still show similarities to the techniques and motifs of the Marquesas.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Their motifs commonly include disembodied parts of the human body (vulvae in particular), animals, plants, ceremonial objects, and boats.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] A prominent motif is also that of the "birdman" figure, which is associated with the *tangata manu* cult of Makemake.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The best-known rock art assemblage of Rapa Nui, however, are the *moai* megaliths.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] A few paintings, mostly of birds and boats, have also been discovered, which are associated with the engravings, rather than being separate artforms.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The rock art in New Zealand can be divided into two regions.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] North Island features more engravings than paintings, while South Island is unique in that it is the only Polynesian island where there are more paintings than engravings.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] New Zealand rock paintings are done in red and black pigments and can sometimes be found at inaccessible heights.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They typically depict human figures (particularly a front-facing human figure with flexed arms), birds, lizards, dogs, fish, and what has been identified as "birdmen".
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Engravings in open spaces like cliffsides are generally of spirals and curvilinear shapes, while engravings in enclosed caves and shelters depict faces and boats.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The same motifs can also be seen in dendroglyphs on living trees.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] These were symbols of status and rank as well as being considered marks of beauty.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] She is probably of Mixed-white ancestry common amongst Maori people, because to her caucasian facial features.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Body art among Austronesian peoples is common, especially elaborate tattooing, which is one of the most well-known pan-Austronesian traditions.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In modern times, tattoos are usually associated with Polynesian culture, due to the highly influential accounts of James Cook in his explorations of the Pacific in the 18th century.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Cook introduced the word "tattoo" (archaic: "tattaow", "tattow") into the English vocabulary from Tahitian and Samoan *tātau* ("to tap").
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] However, tattoos existed prominently in various other Austronesian groups prior to contact with other cultures.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Tattoos had various functions among Austronesian societies.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Among men, they were strongly linked to the widespread practice of head-hunting raids.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In head-hunting societies, tattoos were records of how many heads the warrior had taken in battle, and they were part of the initiation rites into adulthood.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The number and location of tattoos, therefore, were indicative of a warrior's status and prowess.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Among the Indigenous Taiwanese, tattoos were present for both men and women.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Among the Atayal, facial tattoos were dominant.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They indicated maturity and skill in weaving and farming for women and skill in hunting and battle for men.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] As in most of Austronesia, tattooing traditions in Taiwan have largely disappeared due to the Sinicization of native peoples after the Chinese colonization of the island in the 17th century, as well as conversion to Christianity.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Most of the remaining tattoos are only found among elders.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] One of the earliest descriptions of Austronesian tattoos by Europeans was during the 16th-century Spanish expeditions to the Philippines, beginning with the first voyage of circumnavigation by Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The Spanish encountered the heavily tattooed Visayan people in the Visayas Islands, whom they named the *Pintados* (Spanish for "the painted ones").
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] However, Philippine tattooing traditions (*batok*) have mostly been lost as the natives of the islands converted to Christianity and Islam, though they are still practiced in isolated groups in the highlands of Luzon and Mindanao.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Philippine tattoos were usually geometric patterns or stylized depictions of animals, plants, and human figures.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Some of the few remaining traditional tattoos in the Philippines are among elders of the Igorot peoples.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Most of these were records of war exploits against the Japanese during World War II.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Among the Māori of New Zealand, tattoos (*moko*) were originally carved into the skin using bone chisels (*uhi*) rather than through puncturing, as in usual practice.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In addition to being pigmented, the skin was also left raised into ridges of swirling patterns.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Teeth blackening was the custom of dyeing one's teeth black with various tannin-rich plant dyes.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] It was practiced throughout almost the entire range of Austronesia, including Island Southeast Asia, Madagascar, Micronesia, and Island Melanesia, reaching as far east as Malaita.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] It also existed in non-Austronesian populations in Mainland Southeast Asia and Japan.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The practice was primarily preventative, as it reduced the chances of developing tooth decay, similar to modern dental sealants.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] It also had cultural significance and was seen as beautiful.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] A common sentiment was that blackened teeth separated humans from animals.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] For example in Bali, Indonesia, **Potong gigi**, also known as **mesangih** or **mepandes**, is a form of ritual body modification of adolescents, typically teenagers, in parts of Bali that involves the filing of the canine teeth.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The religious traditions of the Austronesian people focus mostly on ancestral spirits, nature spirits, and gods, making it a complex animistic religion.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Mythologies vary by culture and geographical location but share common basic aspects, such as ancestor worship, animism, shamanism, and the belief in a spirit world and powerful deities.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] There is also a great amount of shared mythology and a common belief in Mana.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Many of these beliefs have gradually been replaced.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Examples of native religions include: Indigenous Philippine folk religions (including beliefs in Anito), Sunda Wiwitan, Kejawen, Kaharingan, and Māori religion.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Many Austronesian religious beliefs have been incorporated into foreign religions, such as Hinduism, Buddhism, Christianity, and Islam, which Austronesian peoples were introduced to later.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] With the possible exception of rongorongo on Rapa Nui, Austronesians did not have an indigenous writing system but rather adopted or developed writing systems after contact with various non-Austronesian cultures.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] There existed various forms of symbolic communication using pictograms and petroglyphs, but these did not encode language.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Rongorongo, said to have originally been called *kohau motu mo rongorongo* ("lines of inscriptions for chanting out"), is the only pre-contact indigenous Austronesian system of glyphs that appear to be true writing or at least proto-writing.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They consist of around 120 glyphs, ranging from representations of plants to animals, celestial objects, and geometric shapes.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They were inscribed into wooden tablets about 12 to 20 in (30 to 51 cm) long using shark teeth and obsidian flakes.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The wood allegedly came from toromiro and makoʻi trees, which is notable given that Rapa Nui was completely deforested at the time of European contact.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Of the surviving two dozen tablets, a few were made from trees introduced after European contact, as well as wood originating from European ships and driftwood.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Rapa Nui also has a rich assemblage of petroglyphs largely associated with the *tangata manu* ("birdman") cult of Makemake.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Although some rongorongo glyphs may have been derived from these petroglyphs, rongorongo does not appear in any of the abundant rock carvings in Rapa Nui and seems to be restricted to the wooden tablets.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The tablets were first described by an outsider in 1864 by the Catholic missionary Eugène Eyraud, who said they were found "in all the houses".
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] However, he paid them little attention, and they remained unnoticed by the outside world.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] It wasn't until 1869 that one of the tablets came into the possession of Florentin-Étienne Jaussen, the Bishop of Tahiti.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] He brought the tablets to the world's attention and instructed the Rapa Nui mission to gather more information about them.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] But by then, most of the tablets were allegedly already destroyed, presumed to have been used as fuel by the natives on the deforested island.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] At the time of discovery of the tablets, Rapa Nui had undergone severe depopulation.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] This was largely due to the loss of the island's last trees and the Peruvian and Chilean slave raids in the early 1860s.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The literate ruling classes of the Rapa Nui people (including the royal family and the religious caste) and the majority of the island's population were kidnapped or killed in the slave raids.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Most of those taken died after only one or two years in captivity from harsh working conditions and European diseases.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Succeeding epidemics of smallpox and tuberculosis further decimated the island's population to the point that there were not enough people to bury the dead.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The last remnants of the Rapa Nui people were assimilated by the Tahitians who were later brought to the island in an effort to repopulate it, further resulting in the loss of most of the Old Rapa Nui language.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Oral tradition holds that the ruling classes were the only ones who could read the tablets, and the ability to decipher the tablets was lost along with them.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Numerous attempts have been made to read the tablets, starting from a few years after their discovery.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] But to this day, none have proven successful.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Some authors have proposed that rongorongo may have been an attempt to imitate European script after the idea of writing was introduced during the "signing" of the 1770 Spanish Treaty of Annexation or through knowledge of European writing acquired elsewhere.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They cite various reasons, including the lack of attestation of rongorongo prior to the 1860s, the clearly more recent provenance of some of the tablets, the lack of antecedents, and the lack of additional archaeological evidence since its discovery.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Others argue that it was merely a mnemonic list of symbols meant to guide incantations.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Whether rongorongo is merely an example of trans-cultural diffusion or a true indigenous Austronesian writing system (and one of the few independent inventions of writing in human history) remains unknown.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In Southeast Asia, the first true writing systems of pre-modern Austronesian cultures were all derived from the Grantha and Pallava Brahmic scripts, all of which are abugidas from South India.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Various forms of abugidas spread throughout Austronesian cultures in Southeast Asia as kingdoms became Indianized through early maritime trading.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The oldest use of abugida scripts in Austronesian cultures are 4th-century stone inscriptions written in Cham, from Vietnam.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] There are numerous other Brahmic-derived writing systems among Southeast Asian Austronesians, usually specific to a certain ethnic group.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Notable examples include Balinese, Batak, Baybayin, Buhid, Hanunó'o, Javanese, Kulitan, Lontara, Old Kawi, Rejang, Rencong, Sundanese, and Tagbanwa.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They vary from having letters with rounded shapes to characters with sharp cuneiform-like angles, as a result of the difference in writing mediums, with the former being ideal for writing on soft leaves and the latter on bamboo panels.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The use of the scripts ranged from mundane records to encoding esoteric knowledge on magico-religious rituals and folk medicine.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In regions that converted to Islam, abjads derived from the Arabic script started replacing the earlier abugidas at around the 13th century in Southeast Asia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Madagascar adopted the Arabic script in the 14th century.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Abjads, however, have an even greater inherent problem with encoding Austronesian languages than abugidas, because Austronesian languages have more varied and salient vowels that the Arabic script usually cannot encode.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] As a result, the Austronesian adaptations such as the Jawi and the Pegon scripts have been modified with a system of diacritics that encode sounds, both vowels and consonants, native to Austronesian languages but absent in Semitic ones.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] With the advent of the Colonial Era, almost all of these writing systems have been replaced with alphabets adapted from the Latin, as in the Hawaiian, Filipino, and Malay alphabet.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] However, several Formosan languages had been written in zhuyin, and Cia-Cia off Sulawesi has experimented with hangul.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] On Woleai and surrounding islands, a script was developed for the Woleaian language in the early 20th century.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Approximately 20% of the script's letterforms were borrowed from Latin letters; the remaining characters seem to have been derived from indigenous iconography.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Despite this heavy Latin influence, the script was a syllabary.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Vanuatu has a unique tradition of sand drawing, in which images are created by a single continuous line drawn in the sand.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] It is believed to have functioned as a means of symbolic communication in pre-contact Island Melanesia, especially between travelers and ethnic groups that do not speak the same language.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The sand drawings consist of around 300 different designs and seem to be shared across language groups.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In the 1990s, elements of the drawings were adapted into a modern constructed script called Avoiuli by the Turaga indigenous movement on Pentecost Island.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Genetic studies have been conducted on Austronesian peoples.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Haplogroup O1a, marked by the M119 SNP, is frequently detected in native Taiwanese and northern Filipinos, as well as some people in Indonesia, Malaysia, and non-Austronesian populations in southern China.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] A 2007 analysis of the DNA recovered from human remains in archaeological sites of prehistoric peoples along the Yangtze River in China also shows high frequencies of Haplogroup O1 in the Neolithic Liangzhu culture, linking them to Austronesian and Tai-Kadai peoples.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The Liangzhu culture existed in coastal areas around the mouth of the Yangtze.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Haplogroup O1 was absent in other archaeological sites inland.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The authors of the study suggest that this may be evidence of two different human migration routes during the peopling of Eastern Asia; one coastal and the other inland, with little gene flow between them.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The 'core Austronesian' population derives more ancestry from Late Neolithic Fujian-related sources (66.9%–74.3%), similar to present Kra-Dai groups and southeastern Han Chinese.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Strong affinities also exist between present Austronesians and Qihe3 from Early Neolithic Fujian.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Qihe3 clusters with Boshan from Early Neolithic Shandong and is genetically indistinguishable from Liangdao-2.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] However, Qihe3 could be modeled as a mixture of local ancestries from southeastern China with some input from northeastern China.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In contrast, Late Neolithic Fujianese populations, like Xitoucun and Tanshishan, have higher affinities with Dushan-related populations, who have slightly more affinities for present Austroasiatic-speaking groups.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Likewise, the Taiwan Hanben population is closely related to Dushan-related populations and are related to the Taiwan Gongguan population, Longli Bouyei and Qiandongnan Dong, who are representatives of the ancestral Kra-Dai population, Kinh Vietnamese etc.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Another study states affirms the southeastern Chinese origins of the 'proto-Austronesian' population although there's evidence that they mixed with contemporary populations from Shandong.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Using the Atayal as proxies for the ancestral Austronesian population, they can also be modeled as a mixture of North Indian-related (6%) and Naxi/Miao-related groups (94%).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] An important breakthrough in studies in Austronesian genetics was the identification of the "Polynesian motif" (haplogroup B4a1a1) in 1989, a specific nine-base-pair deletion mutation in mitochondrial DNA.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Several studies have shown that it is shared by Polynesians and Island Southeast Asians, with a sub-branch also identified in Madagascar, indicating shared maternal ancestry among Austronesians.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] This indicates that the Lapita people, the direct ancestors of Polynesians, were likely matrilocal, assimilating Papuan men from outside the community by marriage in Near Oceania, prior to the Polynesian expansion into Remote Oceania.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Moodley *et al.* (2009) identified two distinct populations of the gut bacteria *Helicobacter pylori* that accompanied human migrations into Island Southeast Asia and Oceania, called hpSahul and hspMāori.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The study sampled Native Australians, Native Taiwanese, highlanders in New Guinea, and Melanesians and Polynesians in New Caledonia, which were then compared with other *H. pylori* haplotypes from Europeans, Asians, Pacific Islanders, and others.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The study found hspMāori from Native Taiwanese, Melanesians, Polynesians, and two inhabitants from the Torres Strait Islands, all of which are Austronesian sources.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] As expected, hspMāori showed greatest genetic diversity in Taiwan, while all non-Taiwanese hspMāori populations belonged to a single lineage they called the "Pacific clade".
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They also calculated the isolation-with-migration model (IMa), which showed that the divergence of the Pacific clade of hspMāori was unidirectional from Taiwan to the Pacific.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] This is consistent with the Out-of-Taiwan model of Austronesian expansion.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] A 2014 study states that Austronesian populations from Island Southeast Asia and Oceania, such as Fiji and Polynesia, have 30-90% Taiwan-related ancestry.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Populations from western Island Southeast Asia have ~10–60% H'tin-related ancestry, with the rest being Taiwan-related and Negrito-related.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] In contrast, there is no Taiwan-related ancestry in admixed Mainland Southeast Asian populations that don't traditionally speak Austronesian languages.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The company's scientists surmised that this was due to the shared Austronesian genetic heritage being incorrectly identified as Filipino ancestry.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] According to a 2021 study, Cordillerans are the least admixed Austronesian group among the Austronesians of East Asia, especially Kankanaey, Bontoc, Balangao, Tuwali, Ayangan, Kalanguya, and Ibaloi groups.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Compared to Austronesians like Ami and Atayal, they do not exhibit admixture with Austroasiatic-related and Northeast Asian-related groups.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] All Filipino subgroups likewise show closer affinities to Cordillerans than Ami and Atayal.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Nonetheless, Ami, Atayal and Cordillerans all share strong affinities with Malaysians, Indonesians, Oceanians and even ancient individuals from peninsular Malaysia and Oceanian Lapita.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Cordillerans are also closely related to the ~7,000 to 8,000-y-old Liangdao-2 individual and did not receive the northern East Asian ancestry that was introduced in this individual.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Compared to other Filipino subgroups, Central Cordillerans show no admixture with indigenous Negritos despite extensive interaction with their neighbors.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] However, there's evidence of northern East Asian ancestry being introduced to the Batanes Islands and coastal regions of Luzon after the initial Cordilleran settlement of the Philippines from Taiwan.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] A 2023 study, however, states that present Kankanaey groups have about ~33% northern East Asian ancestry, similar to what's found in Taiwan Highland/Taiwan Orchid Island groups, who have ~28–37% northern East Asian ancestry.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] These findings suggest considerable northern East Asian influence in Taiwan prior to the Out-of-Taiwan expansions.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] For example, other early Out-of-Taiwan (i.e.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Lapita) groups have more northern East Asian ancestry than Into-Taiwan groups (~21–29% vs. ~0–8%).
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Austronesian-related populations also partially contributed to the genomes of Jōmon peoples and Koreans.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] However, the affinities between Austronesians and Jōmon more likely reflect shared descent or genetic input from the Jōmon into Austronesians themselves.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Other studies show no significant gene flow from Austronesians to the Jōmon, including Ryukyuan Jōmon.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The Austronesian migrations were accompanied by a set of domesticated, semi-domesticated, and commensal plants and animals transported via outrigger ships and catamarans that enabled early Austronesians to thrive in their mostly island environments.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Some of these plants are sometimes also known as "canoe plants", especially in the context of Polynesian migrations.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] They provide another source of evidence for Austronesian population movements.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Notable examples of these crops include coconuts, bananas, rice, sugarcane, paper mulberry (tapa tree), breadfruit, taro, ube, areca nut (including the practice of betel chewing), ginger, turmeric, candlenut, pandan, and citruses.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The cultivation of sweet potatoes in Polynesia may also be evidence of prehistoric Austronesian contact with the Americas, though this remains disputed.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] The domesticated animals carried in Austronesian voyages include dogs, pigs, and chickens.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Austronesians also introduced these crops and domesticated animals westward via trade links.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] Island Southeast Asians established spice trade links with the Dravidian-speaking regions in Sri Lanka and Southern India by around 1500 to 600 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] These early contacts resulted in the introduction of Austronesian crops and material culture to South Asia, including betel nut chewing, coconuts, sandalwood, domesticated bananas, sugarcane, cloves, and nutmeg.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] South Asian crops like the mung bean and horsegram were also present in Southeast Asia by 400–100 BCE, indicating the exchange was reciprocal.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] There is also indirect evidence of very early Austronesian contacts with Africa, based on the presence and spread of Austronesian domesticates like bananas, taro, chickens, and purple yam in Africa in the first millennium BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-people-p03] A genomic analysis in 2020 showed Austronesian contact with South America around 1150–1200 CE, the earliest one being between Fatu Hiva and Colombia.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] They range from small dugout canoes to large lashed-lug plank-built vessels.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Their hull configurations include monohulls as well as catamarans and outrigger boats (single-outrigger boats and trimarans).
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Traditional sail types include a variety of distinctively Austronesian crab-claw and tanja configurations, though modern vessels are typically motorized.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] These vessels allowed the migrations of the Austronesian peoples during the Austronesian expansion (starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC from Taiwan and Island Southeast Asia) throughout the islands of the Indo-Pacific, reaching as far as Madagascar, New Zealand, and Easter Island.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] They were also used to establish trading routes, including the Austronesian maritime trade network which formed the maritime leg of the spice trade and later, the maritime silk road.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Austronesians used distinctive sailing technologies, namely the catamaran, the outrigger ship, tanja sail and the crab claw sail.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] This allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region during the Austronesian expansion starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC, and ending with the colonization of Easter Island and New Zealand in the 10th to 13th centuries AD.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Prior to the 16th century Colonial Era, Austronesians were the most widespread ethnolinguistic group, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] They also established vast maritime trading networks, among which is the Neolithic precursor to what would become the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The bottom part consists of a single piece of hollowed-out log.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] These were fitted tightly together edge-to-edge by sewing or with dowels inserted into holes in between, and then lashed to each other with ropes (made from rattan or fibre) wrapped around protruding lugs on the planks.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] They were commonly caulked with pastes made from various plants as well as tapa bark and fibres which would expand when wet, further tightening joints and making the hull watertight.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Shipwrecks of Austronesian ships can be identified from this construction, as well as the absence of metal nails.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] They also independently developed various sail types during the Neolithic, beginning with the crab claw sail (more usually called the "oceanic lateen" or the "oceanic sprit") at around 1500 BCE.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] They are used throughout the range of the Austronesian Expansion, from Maritime Southeast Asia, to Micronesia, Island Melanesia, Polynesia, and Madagascar.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Crab claw sails are rigged fore-and-aft and can be tilted and rotated relative to the wind.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] They evolved from V-shaped perpendicular square sails in which the two spars converge at the base of the hull.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of the crab claw sail (also with the widest distribution) is composed of a triangular sail supported by two light spars (sometimes erroneously called "sprits") on each side.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] They were originally mastless, and the entire assembly was taken down when the sails were lowered.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian rigs were used for double-canoe (catamaran), single-outrigger (on the windward side), or double-outrigger boat configurations, in addition to monohulls.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] There are several distinct types of crab claw rigs, but unlike western rigs, they do not have fixed conventional names.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The need to propel larger and more heavily laden boats led to the increase in vertical sail.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] However this introduced more instability to the vessels.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the unique invention of outriggers to solve this, the sails were also leaned backwards and the converging point moved further forward on the hull.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] This new configuration required a loose "prop" in the middle of the hull to hold the spars up, as well as rope supports on the windward side.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] This allowed more sail area (and thus more power) while keeping the center of effort low and thus making the boats more stable.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The prop was later converted into fixed or removable canted masts where the spars of the sails were actually suspended by a halyard from the masthead.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] This type of sail is most refined in Micronesian proas which could reach very high speeds.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] These configurations are sometimes known as the "crane sprit" or the "crane spritsail".
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Micronesian, Island Melanesian, and Polynesian single-outrigger vessels also used the canted mast configuration to uniquely develop shunting.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] In shunting vessels, both ends are alike, and the boat is sailed in either direction, but it has a fixed leeward side and a windward side.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The boat is shunted from beam reach to beam reach to change direction, with the wind over the side, a low-force procedure.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The bottom corner of the crab claw sail is moved to the other end, which becomes the bow as the boat sets off back the way it came.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The mast usually hinges, adjusting the rake or angle of the mast.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The crab claw configuration used on these vessels is a low-stress rig, which can be built with simple tools and low-tech materials, but it is extremely fast.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] On a beam reach, it may be the fastest simple rig.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Another evolution of the basic crab claw sail is the conversion of the upper spar into a fixed mast.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] In Polynesia, this gave the sail more height while also making it narrower, giving it a shape reminiscent of crab pincers (hence "crab claw" sail).
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] This was also usually accompanied by the lower spar becoming more curved.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The conversion of the prop to a fixed mast in the crab claw sail led to the much later invention of the tanja sail (also known variously and misleadingly as the canted square sail, canted rectangular sail, boomed lugsail, or balance lugsail).
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Tanja sails were rigged similarly to crab claw sails and also had spars on both the head and the foot of the sails; but they were square or rectangular with the spars not converging into a point.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] They are generally mounted on one or two (rarely three or more) bipod or tripod masts, usually made from thick bamboo.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The masts have curved heads with grooves for attaching the halyards.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The lower part of two of the bamboo poles of the mast assembly have holes that are fitted unto the ends of a cross-wise length of timber on the deck, functioning like a hinge.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The forward part of the mast assembly had a forelock.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] By unlocking it, the mast can be lowered across the ship.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] Despite the similarity of its appearance to western square rigs, the tanja is a fore-and-aft rig similar to a lugsail.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The sail was suspended from the upper spar ("yard"), while the lower spar functioned like a boom.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] When set fore-and-aft, the spars extend forward of the mast by about a third of their lengths.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] When running before the wind, they are set perpendicular to the hull, similar to a square rig.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The sail can be rotated around the mast (lessening the need for steering with the rudders) and tilted to move the center of pull forward or aft.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The sail can even be tilted completely horizontally, becoming wing-like, to lift the bow above incoming waves.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The sail is reefed by rolling it around the lower spar.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the tanja sails, ships with the tanja rigs also have bowsprits set with a quadrilateral headsail, sometimes also canted as depicted in the Borobudur ships.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] In the colonial era, these were replaced by triangular western-style jibs (often several in later periods), and the tanja sails themselves were slowly replaced with western rigs like gaff rigs.
[src:djenging/austronesian-vessels] The following is an incomplete list of traditional Austronesian vessels.
[src:djenging/djenging] The djenging is made from a dugout keel (*baran balutu*) built up at the sides with two planks (*tapid* and *lingkam*) attached by dowels.
[src:djenging/djenging] It is usually around 4.5 m (15 ft) long, though it can commonly reach up to 11 m (36 ft) in length.
[src:djenging/djenging] It is usually equal-ended, with the prow and the stern indistinguishable from each other.
[src:djenging/djenging] It has two to four outrigger booms (*batangan*) attached to bamboo floats (*katig*) which are parallel to the main hull.
[src:djenging/djenging] The tips of the floats do not extend beyond the prow and stern.
[src:djenging/djenging] Secondary booms (*sa'am*) also extend from the hull and function as extensions of the removable deck (*lantay*) made of split bamboo.
[src:djenging/djenging] A central house-like structure known as the *palau* is located in the middle, similar to the *vinta* and the *lepa*.
[src:djenging/djenging] The *palau* can be taken down to erect a mast and convert the ship into a sailing ship for transport or fishing.
[src:djenging/djenging] Larger versions of djenging are known as balutu or kubu.
[src:djenging/djenging] They are often permanently moored around anchorages (*sambuangan*).
[src:djenging/djenging] They were elaborately carved with *okil* designs painted with bright colors, with the typical bifurcated extensions on both the prow and the stern known as *buaya* ("crocodile").
[src:djenging/djenging] The house structure of the balutu is known as the *kubu* (hence the name), and unlike in smaller djenging, it is permanently attached.
[src:djenging/djenging] They are propelled by poling or by paddling.
[src:djenging/djenging] Djenging and balutu are very similar to the vinta, but differs mainly in the shape of the hull section and the relative lengths and placement of the outriggers.
[src:djenging/djenging] As of the 1990s, *balutu* have almost completely disappeared among the Sama-Bajau of Tawi-Tawi and the Sulu Archipelago.
[src:djenging/djenging] Djenging have also started to disappear.
[src:djenging/djenging] They are replaced by the outrigger-less lepa, which are easier to sail, as they do not require the house structure to be taken down.
